Now I'll create the 5 questions with careful attention to difficulty levels and proper formatting:

```json
[
  {
    "question": "In Albert Ellis's REBT model, a client experiences intense anxiety (C) after failing a test (A) because they believe 'I must be perfect at everything or I'm worthless' (B). Which component should the therapist primarily target during treatment?",
    "difficulty": "tricky",
    "options": [
      "The activating event (A) - helping the client avoid future test failures",
      "The belief system (B) - challenging the irrational belief about perfection",
      "The consequences (C) - teaching relaxation techniques to reduce anxiety",
      "The disputing process (D) - this is the method, not the target"
    ],
    "answer": "The belief system (B) - challenging the irrational belief about perfection",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "The belief system (B) is the primary target in REBT because Ellis argued that it's the irrational beliefs (not the activating event itself) that cause maladaptive emotional consequences. By disputing and changing these beliefs, the emotional consequences naturally improve. The 'D' (disputing) is the therapeutic technique used to challenge 'B'.",
      "incorrect": {
        "The activating event (A) - helping the client avoid future test failures": "This is incorrect because REBT doesn't focus on changing external events. The model emphasizes that situations themselves don't cause distress - our beliefs about them do. Avoiding tests wouldn't address the underlying irrational belief.",
        "The consequences (C) - teaching relaxation techniques to reduce anxiety": "While managing anxiety symptoms might provide temporary relief, this doesn't address the root cause. REBT targets the beliefs that generate the anxiety, not just the anxiety itself. This would be more aligned with behavioral approaches.",
        "The disputing process (D) - this is the method, not the target": "Disputing (D) is the therapeutic technique or method used in REBT, not the target. It's how the therapist helps challenge the beliefs (B), making B the actual target of intervention."
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "question": "Maria has been diagnosed with depression. She frequently says 'I'm completely incompetent,' 'Nothing ever works out for anyone,' and 'My life will always be this miserable.' According to Aaron Beck's cognitive therapy, which component of the negative triad is Maria NOT explicitly demonstrating?",
    "difficulty": "application",
    "options": [
      "Negative view of self - she clearly sees herself as incompetent",
      "Negative view of the world - she believes nothing works out for anyone",
      "Negative view of the future - she thinks her life will always be miserable",
      "Maria demonstrates all three components of the negative triad"
    ],
    "answer": "Maria demonstrates all three components of the negative triad",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Maria exhibits all three components of Beck's negative triad: (1) Negative view of SELF - 'I'm completely incompetent,' (2) Negative view of WORLD - 'Nothing ever works out for anyone,' and (3) Negative view of FUTURE - 'My life will always be this miserable.' This comprehensive negative thinking pattern is characteristic of depression according to Beck's model.",
      "incorrect": {
        "Negative view of self - she clearly sees herself as incompetent": "This is incorrect because Maria DOES demonstrate a negative view of self when she says 'I'm completely incompetent.' This statement directly reflects the first component of the negative triad.",
        "Negative view of the world - she believes nothing works out for anyone": "This is incorrect because Maria DOES show a negative view of the world with her statement 'Nothing ever works out for anyone.' This reflects a pessimistic worldview beyond just herself.",
        "Negative view of the future - she thinks her life will always be miserable": "This is incorrect because Maria DOES express a negative view of the future when she says 'My life will always be this miserable.' The word 'always' indicates hopelessness about future improvement."
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "question": "A client tells their therapist: 'I walked into the party and nobody came up to talk to me. I thought, \"They all think I'm boring and everyone here dislikes me,\" so I felt anxious and left early.' How would REBT's disputing (D) approach differ from CBT's approach to this situation?",
    "difficulty": "tricky",
    "options": [
      "REBT would focus on challenging the irrational belief as extreme/illogical, while CBT would encourage replacing it with a more balanced, realistic thought",
      "REBT would use behavioral experiments to test the belief, while CBT would only use verbal challenging",
      "REBT would analyze unconscious conflicts, while CBT would focus on conscious thoughts",
      "There is no difference - REBT and CBT use identical techniques"
    ],
    "answer": "REBT would focus on challenging the irrational belief as extreme/illogical, while CBT would encourage replacing it with a more balanced, realistic thought",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "While both approaches address faulty thinking, REBT specifically uses disputing (D) to actively challenge and debate the illogical nature of irrational beliefs ('How do you KNOW everyone dislikes you?'). CBT takes a broader approach by helping clients identify automatic thoughts and replace them with more balanced, realistic alternatives ('Maybe people were busy, or waiting for me to approach them'). CBT also integrates behavioral components more explicitly.",
      "incorrect": {
        "REBT would use behavioral experiments to test the belief, while CBT would only use verbal challenging": "This is backwards. CBT explicitly integrates behavioral experiments and behavioral changes as part of its approach (hence 'Cognitive-Behavioral'). REBT primarily uses verbal disputing and logical challenges, though it can include behavioral elements.",
        "REBT would analyze unconscious conflicts, while CBT would focus on conscious thoughts": "Neither REBT nor CBT analyzes unconscious conflicts - that's psychodynamic therapy. Both REBT and CBT work with thoughts that may be automatic but are accessible to consciousness, not deeply unconscious material.",
        "There is no difference - REBT and CBT use identical techniques": "While related, REBT and CBT have distinct approaches. REBT uses a specific ABCD model with emphasis on disputing irrational beliefs. CBT is broader, integrating cognitive restructuring with explicit behavioral interventions and focusing on interconnected thoughts, feelings, and behaviors."
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "question": "During a therapy session, a client describes their thought process: 'When my boss asked to see me, I immediately felt my heart race and thought, \"I'm getting fired.\" I didn't even question it - the thought just appeared.' According to Beck's cognitive therapy, what type of thought is the client describing?",
    "difficulty": "application",
    "options": [
      "A conscious, deliberate belief that the client carefully considered",
      "An unconscious conflict emerging from childhood experiences",
      "A negative automatic thought that occurred without deliberate reasoning",
      "An irrational belief from the 'B' component of the ABCD model"
    ],
    "answer": "A negative automatic thought that occurred without deliberate reasoning",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "Beck's cognitive therapy specifically identifies these as negative automatic thoughts - they pop into consciousness rapidly without deliberate analysis ('the thought just appeared'), yet they are accessible to awareness (not unconscious). These thoughts are often faulty or exaggerated and occur so quickly that people may not question them initially.",
      "incorrect": {
        "A conscious, deliberate belief that the client carefully considered": "The client explicitly states they 'didn't even question it' and 'the thought just appeared,' indicating this was NOT a deliberate, carefully considered belief. Automatic thoughts occur rapidly and without conscious reasoning.",
        "An unconscious conflict emerging from childhood experiences": "Beck's cognitive therapy focuses on accessible cognitions, not unconscious conflicts (that's psychodynamic therapy). The client is aware of the thought 'I'm getting fired' - it's automatic but not unconscious. Beck emphasized that problematic thoughts are NOT deeply buried in the unconscious.",
        "An irrational belief from the 'B' component of the ABCD model": "While this could be considered an irrational belief, the ABCD model is specifically Ellis's REBT framework, not Beck's cognitive therapy. Beck used different terminology, focusing on 'automatic thoughts' and the 'negative triad' rather than the ABCD structure."
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "question": "A key principle of cognitive therapies is that 'thoughts, not situations, cause maladaptive emotional reactions.' Which scenario best illustrates this principle?",
    "difficulty": "application",
    "options": [
      "Two people experience the same job rejection: Person A thinks 'This wasn't the right fit' and feels disappointed; Person B thinks 'I'm unemployable' and feels devastated",
      "A person with a phobia of dogs feels anxious whenever they see a dog, regardless of their thoughts",
      "A traumatic car accident causes PTSD symptoms in the driver",
      "Taking an SSRI medication reduces someone's depression symptoms"
    ],
    "answer": "Two people experience the same job rejection: Person A thinks 'This wasn't the right fit' and feels disappointed; Person B thinks 'I'm unemployable' and feels devastated",
    "explanation": {
      "correct": "This perfectly illustrates the cognitive principle: the identical situation (job rejection) produces vastly different emotional consequences depending on how each person THINKS about it. Person A's balanced thought leads to mild disappointment, while Person B's catastrophic thought leads to devastation. The situation is the same; the thoughts and resulting emotions differ. This demonstrates that thoughts mediate between situations and emotional reactions.",
      "incorrect": {
        "A person with a phobia of dogs feels anxious whenever they see a dog, regardless of their thoughts": "This answer suggests emotions occur 'regardless of thoughts,' which contradicts the cognitive principle. Actually, cognitive therapists would argue the person HAS anxiety-provoking thoughts about dogs (even if automatic/not fully conscious), such as 'That dog will attack me.' The thoughts may be rapid, but they're present.",
        "A traumatic car accident causes PTSD symptoms in the driver": "While trauma can cause PTSD, this example emphasizes the situation directly causing symptoms without highlighting the role of thoughts/appraisals. Cognitive therapies would focus on how the person thinks about/interprets the trauma and its aftermath, not just the traumatic event itself.",
        "Taking an SSRI medication reduces someone's depression symptoms": "This describes a biological intervention, not a cognitive one. It doesn't illustrate the principle that thoughts (not situations) cause maladaptive reactions. Medication changes brain chemistry directly, whereas cognitive therapy changes thought patterns."
      }
    }
  }
]
```
